# Game Engine Architecture

The game engine is split into focused system files under `src/app/engine/`.

## File Responsibilities

| File | Responsibility |
|------|---------------|
| `engine-types.ts` | Shared interfaces (`IGameEngine`, `Platform`, `Rope`, `DamageNumber`, etc.) |
| `game-engine.ts` | Orchestrator — owns all state, creates systems, runs the game loop |
| `physics-system.ts` | Player movement, gravity, platform/rope collision, climbing |
| `combat-system.ts` | Player attacks, skill execution, buffs, passives, damage to/from zombies, zombie death |
| `zombie-system.ts` | Zombie AI, spawning, waves, corpse management, zombie collisions |
| `projectile-system.ts` | Dragon/spitter projectiles, poison effects |
| `drop-system.ts` | Loot drops, potion use, item collection |
| `vfx-system.ts` | Particles, damage numbers, screen shake/flash, skill animations, hit marks |
| `render-system.ts` | All canvas drawing: background, player, zombies, projectiles, UI overlays |

## System Dependency Rules

- All systems reference the engine state via the `IGameEngine` interface (from `engine-types.ts`).
- Systems never import from `game-engine.ts` — only from `engine-types.ts` and other system files.
- Dependency graph (no circular deps allowed):

```
PhysicsSystem, VfxSystem → standalone
DropSystem → VfxSystem, PhysicsSystem
CombatSystem → VfxSystem, PhysicsSystem, DropSystem
ProjectileSystem → VfxSystem, PhysicsSystem
ZombieSystem → VfxSystem, PhysicsSystem, CombatSystem, ProjectileSystem
RenderSystem → reads state only (no system deps)
```

## Adding New Logic

- Place new gameplay logic in the matching system file.
- If new shared state is needed, add it to `IGameEngine` in `engine-types.ts` and to `GameEngine`.
- Keep `game-engine.ts` as a thin orchestrator — no gameplay logic in the orchestrator.
- New systems should follow the same pattern: constructor takes `IGameEngine` + required peer systems.
